@node Aider context options
@section Aider context options

@vindex gptel-extras-add-repo-map-to-context
The user option @code{gptel-extras-add-repo-map-to-context} controls whether the repository map is automatically added to the @samp{gptel} context before every request sent via @code{gptel-send}. When non-nil, the function @code{gptel-extras-add-context-files} generates (or retrieves from cache) the repository map and injects it into the context (@ref{Automatic context injection}).

The default value is @code{nil}. Enable this option when you are using @samp{gptel} for coding tasks within a project and want the LLM to have an overview of the codebase structure, similar to Aider's built-in repo map feature.

This is a boolean option.

@vindex gptel-extras-add-conventions-to-context
The user option @code{gptel-extras-add-conventions-to-context} controls whether a @samp{conventions.md} file from the project root is automatically added to the @samp{gptel} context before every request. When non-nil, @code{gptel-extras-add-context-files} calls @code{gptel-extras-add-conventions-to-context} to include this file (@ref{Automatic context injection}).

The default value is @code{nil}. Enable this option if your project has a @samp{conventions.md} file documenting coding standards and you want the LLM to respect them.

This is a boolean option.

@vindex gptel-extras-repo-map-cache-ttl
The user option @code{gptel-extras-repo-map-cache-ttl} specifies the time-to-live for cached repository maps, in seconds. After this duration, the cached map is considered stale and will be regenerated on the next request.

The default value is @code{3600} (one hour). Increase this value for large, stable repositories where the structure rarely changes; decrease it for rapidly evolving codebases.

This is an integer option.

@vindex gptel-extras-repo-map-invalidate-on-git-changes
The user option @code{gptel-extras-repo-map-invalidate-on-git-changes} controls whether the repository map cache is invalidated when the git HEAD reference changes, regardless of the TTL@. When non-nil, any new commit, branch switch, or rebase that alters HEAD triggers regeneration of the map.

The default value is @code{t}. Disable this option only if you want the map to persist strictly based on the TTL, ignoring git activity.

This is a boolean option.

@node Email drafting options
@section Email drafting options

@vindex gptel-extras-mu4e-draft-reply-prompt
The user option @code{gptel-extras-mu4e-draft-reply-prompt} specifies the prompt sent to the LLM when drafting an email reply with @code{gptel-extras-mu4e-draft-reply} (@ref{Email drafting with mu4e}). The prompt instructs the model to draft a message based on the attached email thread, complete any partial draft already present, and produce only the body text (no headers or signature).

The default value includes the user's full name (from @code{user-full-name}) to help the LLM identify the sender. Customize this option to adjust the drafting instructions, tone, or language.

This is a string option.

@node Search options
@section Search options

@vindex gptel-extras-search-model
The user option @code{gptel-extras-search-model} specifies the backend and model to use for the AI component of @code{gptel-extras-search-and-ask-model} (@ref{Search integration}). The value is a cons cell of the form @samp{(BACKEND . MODEL)}, where @samp{BACKEND} is a string naming a @samp{gptel} backend and @samp{MODEL} is a symbol identifying the model.

The default value is @samp{("Perplexity" . sonar)}. Change this option if you prefer a different search-oriented model or if the Perplexity backend is not configured.

@vindex gptel-extras-search-prefix
The user option @code{gptel-extras-search-prefix} specifies the URL prefix for the web search opened by @code{gptel-extras-search-and-ask-model}. The query string is appended (URL-encoded) to this prefix.

The default value is @samp{"https://www.google.com/search?q}"=. Change this to use a different search engine (e.g., DuckDuckGo, Bing).

This is a string option.

@node Gemini and VPN options
@section Gemini and VPN options

@vindex gptel-extras-gemini-mullvad-disconnect-after
The user option @code{gptel-extras-gemini-mullvad-disconnect-after} specifies the number of minutes after which the Mullvad VPN connection, activated for a Gemini request, is automatically disconnected (@ref{Model-specific workarounds}).

The default value is @code{1}. Increase this if your Gemini requests take longer than one minute to complete.

This is an integer option.

@node Directory options
@section Directory options

@vindex gptel-extras-dir
The user option @code{gptel-extras-dir} specifies the directory where @samp{gptel} conversation buffers are automatically saved by @code{gptel-extras-save-buffer} (@ref{Saving buffers}). The directory is sorted chronologically via a @samp{.dir-locals.el} file, since the typical use case is to locate a recently modified conversation.

The default value is derived from @code{paths-dir-notes} with @samp{gptel/} appended. Change this if you store your notes elsewhere.

This is a directory option.

@vindex gptel-extras-chatgpt-import-dir
The user option @code{gptel-extras-chatgpt-import-dir} specifies the directory where imported ChatGPT conversations are saved by @code{gptel-extras-import-chatgpt-conversations} (@ref{ChatGPT import}).

The default value is derived from @code{paths-dir-notes} with @samp{chatgpt/} appended.

This is a directory option.

@node Alert options
@section Alert options

@vindex gptel-extras-alert-when-finished
The user option @code{gptel-extras-alert-when-finished} controls whether an alert is displayed after @samp{gptel} finishes inserting a response. It accepts three types of values:

@itemize
@item
@code{t}: always display an alert.
@item
@code{nil}: never display an alert.
@item
A list of model symbols (e.g., @code{(gemini-pro claude-opus-4-6)}): display an alert only when the response comes from one of the listed models.
@end itemize

The default value is @code{nil}. This is useful when using slow models where you might switch to another task while waiting for the response. The alert relies on the @samp{alert} package.

