@node Continuing in a new buffer
@subsection Continuing in a new buffer

@findex gptel-extras-continue-in-new-buffer
Long conversations can become unwieldy and expensive to process. The command @code{gptel-extras-continue-in-new-buffer} creates a new @samp{gptel} buffer whose heading is derived from the current buffer's top-level heading, with a number appended or incremented (e.g., ``My topic'' becomes ``My topic 2'', ``My topic 2'' becomes ``My topic 3'').

The command also inserts a ``Continued here'' link (using Org IDs) at the end of the original buffer, so you can easily navigate between parts of the conversation. The current buffer must have @code{gptel-mode} active.

@node Saving buffers
@subsection Saving buffers

@findex gptel-extras-save-buffer
The function @code{gptel-extras-save-buffer} is designed as @samp{:after} advice on the main @code{gptel} function. When @samp{gptel} is called interactively to create a new buffer (rather than reusing an existing file), this function automatically saves the buffer to @code{gptel-extras-dir} (@ref{Directory options}). The filename is a slugified version of the buffer name with the appropriate extension (@samp{.org} or @samp{.md} depending on the major mode).

In Org mode, the function also inserts the buffer name as a level-1 heading at the top. During the initial save, @code{gptel--save-state} is temporarily removed from @code{before-save-hook} to avoid errors from the incomplete gptel state at that early stage.

@node Recovering from unresponsive sessions
@subsection Recovering from unresponsive sessions

@findex gptel-extras-kill-buffer-then-reopen-file
Occasionally, @samp{gptel} may stop processing requests in a buffer for unclear reasons. The command @code{gptel-extras-kill-buffer-then-reopen-file} works around this by saving the buffer, killing it, and reopening the file. In Org mode buffers, it also unfolds all headings after reopening.

This command can be added to @code{gptel-post-response-functions} for automatic recovery, or invoked manually with @samp{M-x gptel-extras-kill-buffer-then-reopen-file}.

@node ChatGPT import
@section ChatGPT import

@findex gptel-extras-import-chatgpt-conversations
The command @code{gptel-extras-import-chatgpt-conversations} processes the @samp{conversations.json} file included in a ChatGPT data export. It creates one Org file per conversation in @code{gptel-extras-chatgpt-import-dir} (@ref{Directory options}), using a slugified version of the conversation title as the filename.

Each file contains the conversation title as a level-1 heading, with user and assistant messages as level-2 headings beneath it. Markdown content from ChatGPT is converted to Org syntax via Pandoc (using @code{org-extras-convert-markdown-to-org}). A link to the original conversation on the ChatGPT website is included when the conversation ID is available.

With a prefix argument (@samp{C-u}), archived conversations are included in the import. By default, archived conversations are skipped.

@node Email drafting with mu4e
@section Email drafting with mu4e

@findex gptel-extras-mu4e-draft-reply
The command @code{gptel-extras-mu4e-draft-reply} uses the LLM to draft a reply to the email currently being composed in @samp{mu4e} (via @samp{org-msg}). The command adds the entire current buffer as context, positions the cursor after the email headers, and sends the prompt defined in @code{gptel-extras-mu4e-draft-reply-prompt} (@ref{Email drafting options}).

If you have already started writing a partial draft, the LLM will attempt to complete it. The prompt instructs the model to produce only the body text, without headers or signature.

With a prefix argument (@samp{C-u}), the command lets you edit the prompt before sending it, which is useful for providing additional instructions (e.g., requesting a particular tone).

Before sending, the command calls @code{gptel-extras-warn-when-context} (@ref{Context warning}) to alert you if there is existing context that might interfere. After the request is sent, all context is removed.

@node Search integration
@section Search integration

@findex gptel-extras-search-and-ask-model
The command @code{gptel-extras-search-and-ask-model} prompts for a search query, then performs two actions in parallel:

@enumerate
@item
Opens the query in a web browser using @code{gptel-extras-search-prefix} (@ref{Search options}).
@item
Creates a new @samp{gptel} buffer, sets the backend and model to @code{gptel-extras-search-model} buffer-locally, and sends the query as a prompt.
@end enumerate

This is useful for quick research where you want both traditional web results and an AI-generated answer. The command calls @code{gptel-extras-warn-when-context} before proceeding (@ref{Context warning}).

