@node Setting backend and model
@subsection Setting backend and model

@findex gptel-extras-set-backend-and-model
The command @code{gptel-extras-set-backend-and-model} sets @code{gptel-backend} and @code{gptel-model} buffer-locally in the current Org buffer. When called from Lisp, pass the backend name as a string and the model as a symbol. If either argument is nil, the current global value is used.

This is primarily a helper used by other commands such as @code{gptel-extras-run-query} (@ref{Functions}) and @code{gptel-extras-search-and-ask-model} (@ref{Search integration}).

@node Toggling default major mode
@subsection Toggling default major mode

@findex gptel-extras-toggle-major-mode
The command @code{gptel-extras-toggle-major-mode} toggles @code{gptel-default-mode} between @code{org-mode} and @code{markdown-mode}. New @samp{gptel} buffers will use whichever mode is active after the toggle. This does not affect existing buffers.

@node Navigating and sending
@subsection Navigating and sending

@findex gptel-extras-goto-end-and-send
The command @code{gptel-extras-goto-end-and-send} moves point to the end of the current buffer and then calls @code{gptel-send}. This is convenient when you have typed a prompt somewhere in the middle of a buffer and want to ensure the full conversation is sent from the end.

@node Rewriting function definitions
@subsection Rewriting function definitions

@findex gptel-extras-rewrite-defun
The command @code{gptel-extras-rewrite-defun} marks the function definition at point (using @code{mark-defun}) and then invokes @code{gptel-rewrite} on the selected region. This is intended for use with @samp{embark}: binding @code{gptel-rewrite} directly to an Embark action would not work because it requires an active region.

If point is not on a function definition, the command signals an error.

@node Fixing garbled characters
@subsection Fixing garbled characters

@findex gptel-extras-fix-garbled-chars
The command @code{gptel-extras-fix-garbled-chars} replaces @samp{let/} with @samp{let*} and @samp{=(} with @samp{`(} from point to the end of the buffer. These substitutions fix common encoding artifacts that some LLMs introduce when generating Emacs Lisp code.

@node Adding a buffer as context
@subsection Adding a buffer as context

@findex gptel-extras-add-buffer
The command @code{gptel-extras-add-buffer} adds the entire contents of a buffer to the @samp{gptel} context. When called interactively, it adds the current buffer. When called from Lisp, pass a buffer object as the argument.

This is useful when you want the LLM to consider the full content of a file or buffer without manually selecting a region. It is used internally by @code{gptel-extras-mu4e-draft-reply} (@ref{Email drafting with mu4e}).

@node Context warning
@subsection Context warning

@findex gptel-extras-warn-when-context
The command @code{gptel-extras-warn-when-context} checks whether the @samp{gptel} context is non-empty and, if so, prompts for confirmation before proceeding. If the user declines, the command offers to clear the context entirely. This prevents accidentally sending a request with stale or irrelevant context.

This function is called by @code{gptel-extras-mu4e-draft-reply} (@ref{Email drafting with mu4e}) and @code{gptel-extras-search-and-ask-model} (@ref{Search integration}).

@node Connecting to MCP servers
@subsection Connecting to MCP servers

@findex gptel-extras-connect-to-all-servers
The command @code{gptel-extras-connect-to-all-servers} connects to all configured MCP (Model Context Protocol) servers via @code{gptel-mcp-connect}, then immediately applies the @samp{tools-clear} preset to deactivate all tools. This is useful during initialization: it establishes the server connections so that tools are available on demand, without activating any tools by default.

